    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Essential concepts}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        As mentioned in the introduction,
    </p>
    <p>
        Complementary angles are two angles that add up to <m>90^\circ</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, if <m>y</m> is one angle and <m>x</m> is the other angle, then:
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow>y+x =\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Generally,For any two complementary angles <m>x </m> and <m>y</m>, the following relationships hold:
    </p>

    <p>
        <m>sin\,x=cos\,y</m> and <m>cos\,x=sin\,y</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        This means that the sine of one angle is equal to the cosine of the other, and vice versa.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find acute angles <m>\theta</m> and <m>\beta</m> if:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\,45^\circ=sin\,\alpha</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\,\beta=sin\,5\beta</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>sin\,2\alpha=cos\,30^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\,45^\circ=sin\,\alpha</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Implies that, <md>
                                <mrow> 45^\circ+\alpha=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  90^\circ -45^\circ</mrow>
                                 <mrow> =\amp 45^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\,\beta=sin\,5\beta</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Implies that, <md>
                                <mrow> \beta+5\beta=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> 6\beta=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> \beta=\amp\frac{90^\circ}{6} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 15^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>sin\,2\alpha=cos\,30^\circ</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Implies that, <md>
                                <mrow> 2\alpha+30^\circ=\amp 90^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> 2\alpha=\amp 90^\circ-30^\circ </mrow>
                                <mrow> \alpha=\amp \frac{60^\circ}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 30^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
        
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are complementary angles.If <m>A=\frac{1}{2}B</m>, find:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(A)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>sin\,A</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\,A</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                When we say <m>A \,\text{and} \,B</m> are complimentary it implies that, <m>A+B=90^\circ</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Also we have, <m>A=\frac{1}{2}B</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                First, Write <m>A</m> interms of  <m>A</m> that is,
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>A= \amp \frac{1}{2}B</mrow>
                    <mrow>B= \amp 2A </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since, <m>A+B=90^\circ</m>, subtitute <m>B=2A</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> A+2A=\amp  90^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> 3A=\amp  90^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow>A= \amp \frac{90^\circ}{3}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 30^\circ </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>sin\,A=\amp sin\,30^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Use tables of sine to find <m>sin\,30^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>sin\,30^\circ=0.5000</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, <m>sin\,A=0.5000</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>cos\,A=\amp cos\,30^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Use tables of cosine to find <m>cos\,30^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos \,30^\circ=0.8660</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, <m>cos\,A=0.8660</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In the figure below, <m>DE = 15 \,cm</m> and
                <m>DC = 25\, cm</m>. Find:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>sin\, \alpha</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\, \alpha</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Triangle16">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[blue]
                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,3);
                    \coordinate (B) at (4,3);
                    \coordinate (C) at (4,0);

                    % Draw triangle
                    \draw [very thick,fill=pink] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Mark right angle
                    \draw [very thick] (B) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,-0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                    % Label points
                    \node[left] at (A) {D};
                    \node[above] at (B) {E};
                    \node[right] at (C) {F};

                    % Draw angle arc
                    \draw (A) ++(0.3,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=-40, radius=0.3];
                    \node [right]at (0.4,2.8) {$\alpha$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Recall: <m>sin\, \alpha=\frac{\text{opp}}{\text{Hyp}}=\frac{EF}{25\,cm}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            But, <md>
                                <mrow> EF^2=\amp 25^2-15^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 400</mrow>
                                <mrow>  EF=\amp  \sqrt{400}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 20 \,cm </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore,<md>
                                <mrow> sin\, \alpha= \amp \frac{20}{25} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  \frac{4}{5}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 0.8 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>cos\,\alpha=\frac{adj}{Hyp}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> cos \, \alpha=\amp \frac{15}{25} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{3}{5} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 0.6 </mrow>
                                
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
